    </exercise>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Consolidation</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_s2txhybw">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_hj4jxluy">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ep4pdvy9">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_cih781sb">
                    To practice expanding and factoring perfect square trinomials using the identities.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_basz5ucf">
                <title>Worked Example</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_182rkw1o">
                    <alert>Factor <m>x^2 + 6x + 9</m>:</alert>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_xjl9gfsm">
                    <alert>Step 1:</alert> <m>x^2</m> is a perfect square (<m>\sqrt{x^2} = x</m>), <m>9</m> is a perfect square (<m>\sqrt{9} = 3</m>), and <m>6x = 2 \times x \times 3 = 2ab</m> ✓.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_im4l447e">
                    <alert>Step 2:</alert> <m>a = x</m>, <m>b = 3</m>.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_1pzz2m6w">
                    <alert>Step 3:</alert> <m>x^2 + 6x + 9 = (x+3)^2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_pyxpprg8">
                <title>More Practice</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_cudtby50">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_5mtlc086"><m>x^2 - 10x + 25 = (x-5)^2</m> (negative middle term).</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o4j2icsl">Expand <m>(2x+5)^2 = 4x^2 + 20x + 25</m>.</li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_7voowz8h"><m>4y^2 + 12y + 9</m>: <m>a = 2y</m>, <m>b = 3</m>, <m>12y = 2(2y)(3)</m> ✓ <m>\rightarrow (2y+3)^2</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_hp6yvlpr">
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_t74h7y27">
                    The teacher emphasizes the three-step check: (1) Is the first term a perfect square? (2) Is the last term a perfect square? (3) Does the middle term equal twice the product of the square roots?
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-perfect-squares-identity">
        <exercise xml:id="auto_9xtjrij9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_eex5i112">
                    Expand and simplify the following expressions:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_w470x8u5">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_wsgufief"><m>(x + 7)^2</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_2g7lsu00"><m>(3a - 2)^2</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_07yqw5b9"><m>(2m + 5n)^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_jbnsfdtq">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_1dxct07l"><m>x^2 + 14x + 49</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_xlm4fhhc"><m>9a^2 - 12a + 4</m></li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_l7i2et3o"><m>4m^2 + 20mn + 25n^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="auto_p4c31rbq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_m6k18jjv">
                    Show that <m>x^2 - 10x + 25</m> is a perfect square and write it in factorized form.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_gx1jko54">
                    <m>
                    x^2 - 10x + 25 = (x - 5)^2
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_ns0uxczo">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_k321dz6w">
                    Factorize: <m>16y^2 + 40y + 25</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_d25m68tl">
                    <m>
                    16y^2 + 40y + 25 = (4y + 5)^2
                    </m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_gj8bpweq">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_ashz5d4d">
                    Determine whether <m>4x^2 + 12x + 7</m> is a perfect square. Give a reason for your answer.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p xml:id="auto_m09wfd53">
                    It is not a perfect square because 
                    <m>4x^2 = (2x)^2</m> and 
                    <m>7</m> is not a perfect square, 
                    and the middle term <m>12x</m> does not match 
                    <m>2(2x)(\sqrt{7})</m>. 
                    Therefore, it cannot be written in the form <m>(a+b)^2</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_2i7ravxz">
                <title>Questions</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_q30te2w1">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_yr349ky8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_vsmghwgt">
                                Factor:
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_dx6atwkm"><m>x^2 + 8x + 16</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_5jnw2dyh"><m>x^2 - 14x + 49</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_o8fb63j6"><m>9a^2 + 6a + 1</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_esm8c1y4">
                            <p xml:id="auto_c03nrdv9">
                                Expand:
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_wxxt4rf8"><m>(x+4)^2</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_1ecusd02"><m>(3y-2)^2</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_4yxo1ovq">
                            <p xml:id="auto_ydf44njl">
                                Is <m>x^2 + 5x + 6</m> a perfect square trinomial? If yes, factor it.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_whz19gb7">
                            <p xml:id="auto_fqigoayr">
                                A square tile has sides of length <m>(x+2)</m> cm. Write the area in expanded form.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_79c7toog">
                            <p xml:id="auto_2bkekca0">
                                Complete: <m>x^2 + 10x + \underline{\hspace{1cm}} = (x + \underline{\hspace{1cm}})^2</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_uv2jj9qw">
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_jjnrldm1">
                    <ol>
                        <li xml:id="auto_o7gm1zdg">
                            <p xml:id="auto_yv2a0tps">
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_y93ek1yu"><m>(x+4)^2</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_oxjqmr99"><m>(x-7)^2</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_umvomd6c"><m>(3a+1)^2</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_uuhpx6o1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_awox30oy">
                                <ol marker="(a)">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_3p4thtst"><m>x^2 + 8x + 16</m></li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_jza92yae"><m>9y^2 - 12y + 4</m></li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_00p4946k">
                            <p xml:id="auto_jyly7l3o">
                                NOT a perfect square <mdash/> the middle term should be approximately <m>4.9x</m>, not <m>5x</m>. It factors as <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_v5m2ouc8">
                            <p xml:id="auto_bzrsd8vw">
                                <m>x^2 + 4x + 4</m> cm<m>^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_jcp2bfxr">
                            <p xml:id="auto_r3qwedzx">
                                <m>25</m>, <m>(x+5)^2</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>
    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation and Extension</title>
        <table xml:id="auto_qmdt7vpz">
            <tabular halign="left">
                <col width="20%"/>
                <col width="55%"/>
                <col width="25%"/>
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Learner Level</cell>
                    <cell>Strategies / Activities</cell>
                    <cell>Resources</cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide identity reference cards. Use color coding to distinguish <m>a^2</m>, <m>2ab</m>, and <m>b^2</m>. Start with numerical examples (e.g., <m>4 + 4 + 1 = 9 = 3^2</m>). Pair with a peer for guided support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert></line>
                        <line>1. Factor <m>x^4 + 4x^2 + 4</m>.</line>
                        <line>2. If <m>(x+k)^2 = x^2 + 12x + c</m>, find <m>k</m> and <m>c</m>.</line>
                        <line>3. Complete the square: <m>x^2 + 6x + 5 = 0</m>.</line>
                        <line>4. Prove <m>(a+b+c)^2 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 2ab + 2bc + 2ac</m>.</line>
                        <line></line>
                        <line><alert>Solutions:</alert></line>
                        <line>1. <m>x^4 + 4x^2 + 4 = (x^2)^2 + 2(x^2)(2) + 2^2 = (x^2+2)^2</m>.</line>
                        <line>2. <m>2k = 12 \rightarrow k = 6</m>, <m>c = k^2 = 36</m>.</line>
                        <line>3. <m>x^2 + 6x + 5 = 0 \rightarrow x^2 + 6x + 9 = 4 \rightarrow (x+3)^2 = 4 \rightarrow x + 3 = \pm 2 \rightarrow x = -1</m> or <m>x = -5</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>

